{
  "answer": "The *matla* (opening couplet) of Mirza Ghalib's ghazal from *Diwan-e-Ghalib* reads, in the original Urdu:\n\n> حیراں ہوں دل کو روؤں کہ پیٹوں جگر کو میں  \n> مقدور ہو تو ساتھ رکھوں نوحہ_گر کو میں[^1]\n\nIn Roman transliteration:\n\n> Hairaan hoon dil ko roun ke peetun jigar ko main  \n> Maqdoor ho to saath rakhun nauha-gar ko main[^2]\n\nIn English translation:\n\n> Should I now mourn my heart, or my own soul now tear?  \n> If I had means, I’d keep a hired mourner near me.[^3]\n\nThe speaker faces the anguished dilemma of whether to weep (*roun*) for his shattered heart (*dil*)—the seat of love and emotion—or to violently tear/beat (*peetoon*) his innermost liver/soul (*jigar*) in raw grief, expressing utter bewilderment (*hairan hoon*) at such profound inner devastation.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/65-hairaan-hoon-dil-ko-roun-ke-peetun-jigar-ko-main/original/#p-cfda65).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/65-hairaan-hoon-dil-ko-roun-ke-peetun-jigar-ko-main/transliteration/#p-509dee).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/65-hairaan-hoon-dil-ko-roun-ke-peetun-jigar-ko-main/translation/#p-a750b7).",
